# Pattern: app deploy CI — "push to main → rollout", no cluster access

How an app you build yourself ships new versions **without ever touching the
cluster**. The app's own CI builds the image and writes the new tag into its
`deploy/overlays/production` overlay; Argo CD (registered via
`scripts/new-app.sh`) pulls that overlay and rolls the Deployment forward.

This is the counterpart to the cluster-side wiring: `new-app.sh` gives Argo CD an
`Application` pointing at `deploy/overlays/production` in the app repo. This
pattern is what populates the image tag there.

**Invariants this honors:** no stored kubeconfig, no `kubectl` in CI, no
`id-token` for the cluster (inv. 1 + 2); native-arch builds, never QEMU (inv. 4).

In the snippets below replace `<owner>` (your GitHub owner, `{{ github_owner }}`)
and `<app>` with the app's name.

## Layout in the app repo

```
deploy/overlays/production/
  kustomization.yaml      # resources + an images: block CI rewrites
  deployment.yaml         # image: ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>  (bare, no tag)
  service.yaml
  ingress.yaml            # cert-manager.io/cluster-issuer: acme
  sealed-<app>-oidc.yaml  # app-bound secrets only (see app-native-oidc)
```

`deploy/overlays/production/kustomization.yaml`:

```yaml
apiVersion: kustomize.config.k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Kustomization
resources:
  - deployment.yaml
  - service.yaml
  - ingress.yaml
  - sealed-<app>-oidc.yaml
images:
  - name: ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>
    newTag: latest   # CI overwrites this with the git SHA on every push
```

## The workflow (`.github/workflows/deploy.yml`)

Build each arch on its **native** runner, merge into one manifest, then commit
the tag bump. The bump commit carries `[skip ci]` so it does not re-trigger the
workflow (otherwise: push → build → commit → push → build … forever).

{% raw %}
```yaml
name: Deploy
on:
  push:
    branches: [main]

permissions:
  contents: write   # to commit the tag bump
  packages: write   # to push the image

jobs:
  build-amd64:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - uses: docker/login-action@v3
        with: { registry: ghcr.io, username: ${{ github.actor }}, password: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }} }
      - run: |
          docker build -t ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>:${{ github.sha }}-amd64 .
          docker push ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>:${{ github.sha }}-amd64

  build-arm64:
    runs-on: ubuntu-24.04-arm        # native arm64 runner — NEVER QEMU
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - uses: docker/login-action@v3
        with: { registry: ghcr.io, username: ${{ github.actor }}, password: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }} }
      - run: |
          docker build -t ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>:${{ github.sha }}-arm64 .
          docker push ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>:${{ github.sha }}-arm64

  deploy:
    needs: [build-amd64, build-arm64]
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - uses: docker/login-action@v3
        with: { registry: ghcr.io, username: ${{ github.actor }}, password: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }} }
      - name: Assemble multi-arch manifest
        run: |
          SHA=${{ github.sha }}
          docker buildx imagetools create -t ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>:$SHA \
            ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>:$SHA-amd64 \
            ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>:$SHA-arm64
      - name: Bump tag in overlay & commit
        run: |
          curl -sSL https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/kustomize/releases/download/kustomize%2Fv5.4.3/kustomize_v5.4.3_linux_amd64.tar.gz | tar xz -C /usr/local/bin
          cd deploy/overlays/production
          kustomize edit set image ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>=ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>:${{ github.sha }}
          cd -
          git config user.name  "deploy-bot"
          git config user.email "deploy-bot@users.noreply.github.com"
          git add deploy/overlays/production/kustomization.yaml
          git diff --staged --quiet || git commit -m "chore(deploy): ${{ github.sha }} [skip ci]"
          git push
```
{% endraw %}

There is **no `kubectl`, no `KUBECONFIG`, no `id-token: write`** anywhere — the
production deploy never authenticates to the cluster. PR previews are pull-based
too: Argo CD's PullRequest generator deploys each open PR and prunes it on close
(`patterns/app-preview-prs/`), so CI never talks to the cluster at all.

## Database migrations (single-replica apps)

With one replica there is no migration-job orchestration to get right: run
migrations in an **init container** on the Deployment, sharing the data volume,
using the same image as the app container (the `images:` transformer rewrites
both):

```yaml
initContainers:
  - name: migrate
    image: ghcr.io/<owner>/<app>   # same tag as the app, set by kustomize
    command: ["/app/migrate"]
    volumeMounts: [{ name: data, mountPath: /data }]
```

Migrations run once per rollout, before the app starts; a failed migration
crashes the rollout instead of serving a half-migrated app.

## Alternative: Argo CD Image Updater

If an app's overlay lives **in this GitOps repo** (not in the app repo), the app
CI cannot commit the tag. Run [Argo CD Image
Updater](https://argocd-image-updater.readthedocs.io/) instead: annotate the
`Application` with an image alias and an update strategy, and the updater watches
the registry and bumps the tag — either by patching the live Application or by
writing back to git (`write-back-method: git`, which needs a git credential with
**write** access and a sortable tag the strategy can order). Prefer the
app-CI-commits-the-tag pattern above when the app owns its overlay — it needs no
extra component or write credential.
